Question: How to use an iterator in this case?: :I have to iterate through an arraylist in this manner.ArrayList<Integer> li = new ArrayList<Integer>();li.add(20);li.add(30);li.add(40);li.add(50);li.add(70);for (int i = 0; i < li.size() - 1; i++)    System.out.println(li.get(i) + " " + li.get(i + 1));Output:20 3030 4040 5050 70How to do the same using an iterator?
Please using this api: Iterator.next.
Answer:<<<api>>>: Iterator.next
<<<code>>>: ArrayList<Integer> li = new ArrayList<Integer>();
li.add(20);
li.add(30);
li.add(40);
li.add(50);
li.add(70);
Iterator<Integer> it = li.iterator();
while (it.hasNext()) {
    if (it.hasNext()) {
        System.out.println(it.next() + " " + it.next());
    }
}
<<<explanation>>>: The next() method in the Iterator interface is used to get the next element in the iteration. This method throws a NoSuchElementException if there are no more elements in the iteration.
Question: How can I sort an array in descending order in Java?
Please using this api: Arrays.sort.
Answer:<<<api>>>: Arrays.sort
<<<code>>>: int[] array = {5, 2, 8, 1, 9};
Arrays.sort(array);
for (int i = array.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    System.out.print(array[i] + " ");
}
<<<explanation>>>: The sort() method of the Arrays class sorts the specified array of objects into ascending numerical order. The for loop is used to print the array in descending order.
